So cute! But this is a real business  .   95% of the time there will be NO customer ready to pop out and greet the bot at the moment of delivery  .   The FedEx Bot is the clear winner from my perspective  .   It has superior navigation skills, which are the hardest and most expensive piece for any bot  .   A SUPER requirement for delivering large/heavy boxes right up to someone's front door  .   A suitable bot must be able to navigate any and all kinds of surface terrain (dirt, small stones, crushed seashells) in any weather (rain/snow/ice) walking on possibly unclear paths and coming up against objects such as toys, landscaping bushes, flowers, deciding whether to try to clear the path or go around an object, then finally make its way down or up stairways/stairwells, irregular stone stairs, steep steps made of everything from slippery composite boards, to old/cracked/broken wood/concrete material, and position itself right up to that front or side door to drop the package in a manner that is safe  .   Small details such as whether the front door opens IN or opens OUT will determine whether any portion of the package can be left in the path of an OUTWARD swinging front door  .   The most common front door consists of a large cement set of 2 or 3 steps where the cement stairs is usually only a few inched wider than the door itself, making it dangerous or impossible to leave most large and/or heavy packages on the top landing of the front door cement steps IF the outermost front door opens OUTWARD, because it would hit the package and either push it off the stairs flying (if lightweight), or prevent the customer from coming out the front door to retrieve their package (if package is heavy)  .
